  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Addressing Capacity Gaps of the Thet Kel Pyin Sub Rural Health Center in Providing Life-Saving Health Care Services</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to assist the State Health Department (SHD) in Rakhine in improving the overall services and expanding the operating hours at the Thet Kel Pyin Sub-Rural Health Center (TKP-SRHC) through: (a) the deployment of at least the minimum   (suggested number is 8) required doctors and health workers to augment existing SHD and NGO human resources (b) training of all   SRHC staff from SHD, MERCY Malaysia and IRC, both medical and non-medical, on Protection, Gender Based Violence, and Reproductive, Maternal and Child Health, MHPSS and PFA*  and a Resilient Health Facility and (c) upgrade and/or repair and maintenance of the TKP-SRHC to meet the minimum standards in terms of physical facility  (including upgrading works to increase accessibility to the SRHC for PWDs), equipment and human resources including increasing the number of rotating shifts, improving the SRHC&#x2019;s systems such as patient recording, health waste management, logistics, etc. The doctors and health workers to be deployed and trained under this project (all Myanmar nationals with technical assistance from MERCY health specialists) are envisaged to be eventually taken in by the SHD in the government&#x2019;s effort to fill up all &#x201C;sanctioned&#x201D; positions and reduce the vacancies in the government&#x2019;s health system. Due to Myanmar&#x2019;s MOH health policies, only SHD appointed staff are allowed to do immunizations, however, they request for assistance from I/NGO&#x2019;s working in the area to join in the programs. Because of this, trainings on immunization can also only be done by the SHD.

*Mental Health and Psychosocial Support Service and Psychological First Aid.</narrative>
  </description>
